column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

The adverse and extreme weather conditions saw numbers reduce as agents offered 645 liveweight cattle. Quality was again extremely mixed with female cattle again making up the bulk of the offering with 209 cows 172 heifers and 231 steers on offer. The usual trade and processor buyers, feeders and restockers provided steady competition and while yearling steers eased up to 10c/kg the grown steers , heifers and medium to heavy cows lifted by 10c to 20c/kg.

Vealer steers sold from 240c to 320c with heifers selling from 205c to 340c/kg. Yearling steers sold from 240c to 345c with heifers fetching 167c to 270c/kg.

Manufacturing steers sold from 289c to 290c as grown steers ranged from 240c to 349c with heifers fetching 200c to 339c/kg. Light dairy cows sold from 130c to 215c with beef breeds selling from 150c to 261c/kg. Medium dairy cows sold from 197c to 223c as beef types ranged from 160c to 320c. Heavy dairy cows sold from 160c to 233c with beef breeds selling from 255c to a top of 347c/kg. Bulls sold from 220c to 280c/kg.

Market reporter: John Traeger.
